<br>
<br>
el <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/brage81292.showUserPublicProfile?gid=witherweaver>Witherweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Math Wiz</span><br>  Posts: 1104<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 3:37:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=737.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wee Math Question</span><hr size=1> By &quot;resisdes in a triangle&quot; I'll assume you mean is contained within the interior, but not the edges.<br>
<br>
Assume you have a triangle at the points (x1,y1), (x2,y2), and (x3,y3) in the standard cartesian coordinate plane.<br>
<br>
Then you can form three lines that make the triangle:<br>
<br>
L1: (y-y1) = (y2-y1)/(x2-x1)*(x-x1)<br>
L2: (y-y1) = (y3-y1)/(x3-x1)*(x-x1)<br>
L3: (y-y2) = (y3-y2)/(x3-x2)*(x-x2)<br>
<br>
Then you can express the triangle as an inequality.  The interior of the triangle will be something like:<br>
<br>
{(x,y): (y-y1) &gt;  (y2-y1)/(x2-x1)*(x-x1) <br>
AND     (y-y1) &lt; (y3-y1)/(x3-x1)*(x-x1)<br>
AND     (y-y2) &lt; (y3-y2)/(x3-x2)*(x-x2)}<br>
<br>
Or something like that.  The specific inequalities will depend on what points you let be x1,y1,x2,y2, etc, and where in the plane it is.<br>
<br>
So you can simply test if your point is satisfied by those inequalities (i.e. if it's in the interior of three lines).<br>
<br>
That's one method, I'll think about the other one in a bit.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p>Witherweaver Wyntari<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->65 Arcanist<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=113163">Witherweaver Wyntari's Profile</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/brage81292.showUserPublicProfile?gid=witherweaver>Witherweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Math Wiz</span><br>  Posts: 1105<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 3:54:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=737.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wee Math Question</span><hr size=1> Okay here's a more geoemetrical approach.  Take your triangle and your point, connect the vertices of your triangle to the point.<br>
<br>
You now have three new triangles.  If you sum up the areas of those triangles and it is not equal to the area of the original triangle, then your point lies outside of the triangle (because, if the point is inside the the three triangles that are formed combine to give you the total triangle).<br>
<br>
However I'm not 100% sure that you couldn't have a point outside the triangle in the correct place so that the sum of the areas just happens to equal the area of the original triangle, so this is a necessary, but perhaps not sufficient condition.<br>
<br>
So I'll have to think about that, or maybe someone can help out.  But that could be a good place to start.<br>
<br>
 <p>Witherweaver Wyntari<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->65 Arcanist<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=113163">Witherweaver Wyntari's Profile</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/brage81292.showUserPublicProfile?gid=witherweaver>Witherweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Math Wiz</span><br>  Posts: 1107<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 4:25:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=737.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wee Math Question</span><hr size=1> K, second method works if you think about it.  Draw a triangle, draw any point outside, draw the lines from the vertices to that point and you have three new triangles that come together to form a triangle that encompases your original one, and hence the area will be larger.<br>
<br>
So the only way for the point to lie inside is if the areas are equal.<br>
<br>
Also on the first method, you run into a problem if you have a verticle line anywhere, but that's easy to check for and modify (if the x value of your point lies to the left/right of your verticle line, whichever side is interior to the triangle, then use that instead of testing the y-values).<br>
<br>
